<DOC><DOCNO> AP881111-0200 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1943EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-11 0515</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0527</SECOND><HEAD>Snow Falls in the Rockies</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Snow fell Friday in the Rocky Mountains, dumping 10 inches onSummitville in southern Colorado and whitening the ski slopes atAlta, Utah, with 6 inches.   Most of the nation had dry, seasonably cool weather, but showersand thunderstorms struck northern Texas and southern Oklahoma, andthere was rain at the lower elevations of Colorado and northwesternNew Mexico.   A snow advisory was in effect for the mountains of Colorado andsouth-central mountains of Wyoming, where 4 to 6 more inches of snowwas expected at elevations above 8,000 feet.   The storm, one of several from the Pacific that have brought snowto the Colorado mountains this week, was accompanied by winds thatat times reduced visibility and made driving hazardous on mountainpasses.   The Colorado Avalanche Information Center said the recentsnowstorms already have raised the snowpack in the northern Coloradomountains to 2 to 3 feet, with drifts of 4 to 5 feet abovetimberline.   Brisk southeastery winds accompanied the dry air across much ofthe central United States, while blustery northwest winds blewacross New England. Gale warnings continued in effect along thecoast of Washington and Oregon.   The Southeast and Southwest enjoyed sunny skies with temperaturesin the 60s and 70s. In the North, temperatures rose only into the30s in the upper Mississippi Valley and Great Lakes region andreached the 40s in the northern Plains. Southern Florida and extremesouthern Texas warmed into 80s.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 26degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 88 degrees at Harlingen, Texas.   The low for the nation early Friday was 16 degrees at Mason City,Spencer and Waterloo, all in Iowa.   Lights in the sky over Vermont early Friday were believed to havebeen one of two families of meteorites that are visible during themiddle of November.   It was 48 years ago on Nov. 11 that a blizzard struck the GreatLakes and upper Midwest, killing more than 154 people, including 59dead in shipwrecks on Lake Michigan. Up to 17 inches of snow fell inIowa, where thousands of cattle died, and whole towns were isolatedby huge snowdrifts.   For Saturday, the National Weather Service forecast called forshowers and thunderstorms from central Texas and eastern Oklahomaacross the Tennessee Valley and the central Gulf Coast states; rainfrom the middle and upper Mississippi Valley across the Ohio Valleyand the Great Lakes region, with snow near Lake Superior. In theWest, rain was forecast from the northern and central Pacific coastacross the northern half of the Plateau. Fair to partly sunny skieswere expected elsewhere.   High temperatures were predicted in the 40s across most of thenorthern United States, but with highs only in the upper 30s fromMinnesota to upper Michigan and in northern Maine; above 70 fromSouthern California through much of Texas to Florida and southernGeorgia, with highs in the 80s in south-central Texas and theFlorida peninsula; in the 50s and 60s elsewhere.</TEXT></DOC>